commentText: I think the reason the trash is everywhere is because of all the wind blowing it around. At least that was the conclusion that I came up with. My family and I lived in Midland for 3 years, from 2014 to 2017. We move there because my husband is in the oil field, And we were trying to keep the family together.  I have to agree with you everyone I spoke to prior to movin told me not to do it and that it was a horrible place.  Needless to say I was looking over my shoulder for about the 1st year waiting on something horrible to happen , thank God,   it never did.  We really liked Midland ,the people were nice, The food was good, And the weather was uneventful. Coming from Louisiana that was a good thing !  We had a sun in middle school at the time he had no problems there except for the lack of entertainment for school age kids.  In my opinion they could really benefit from a waterpark , or an amusement park, even  just a  Go kart track or Mini golf course would be nice. The other negative that I found was how far Midland Texas is from , well.... everything !   It really is in the middle of nowhere . So,  aside from being in the middle of the desert, and the cost of living being expensive,  It's not a bad place to call home, at least for a little while.

commentText: Born and raised here.  Came back in 1983.  When oil was at $100 it was not fun living here....too much traffic and crazy driving people.  Now, with oil at $60, things are much better.  There are still plenty of opportunities and CDL drivers are still needed.  You can still make good money here.  Schools, drugs, crime on par with a lot of other places so not really an added negative.   A lot of dedicated teachers for sure.  Roads are getting upgraded thanks to the decreased oil prices which have provided less traffic and more opportunities to improve roads.    Your quality of life and your income provide a good life.  You can degrade your life with your money anywhere, it's no different or worse here.   It's easy to see sunsets here and you don't have to look at the oil slick in the pavement to see a rainbow.  Out here you can see the whole thing and appreciate it!  Wind is bad and of all the negatives, I have to say I hate the wind more than anything.  None the less, with retirement about 2 years away, I'll probably stay in Midland.....good people, quality people, safe living.

commentText: Good video, informative and gives a good idea for that type of work, if you have driving experience. My freind is trying to get me interested in this type of driving (he's in driving school and says it's all the rage rn through the trucking grapevine, but think he just wants my peer support for his new adventure) in maybe any kind of driving work in that hydrofrac well industry,doing my homework and video is pretty informative. I had 13 years big rig  driving experience, did OTR first, route restaraunt work, worked at a giant ltl hub where I moved a volume of 100 to 150 trailers per shift, plus p&d and line haul, before I hauled doubles (it was the best! Or my favorite job out of all)   but got a D.U.I. (was in my personal vehicle, wasn't pulled over for suspicion of drunk driving but had a headlight out and didn't plead the 5th when the officer asked if I had anything to drink, thought I was good for the b.a.c test but was just over enough to make it count,  still guilty so not excusing myself with the details) 4 years ago but coming up on 5 years in July from conviction date.  Lost my  job hauling doubles for 6 years. My licence was suspended for a year but was able to get my CDL back with all my endorsements (I had all of them). I was eligble for an expungement, because I was a first time offender, and told by lawyer it won't show up on criminal background check, and I am legally allowed not to disclose that on any job application for a job that doesn't require driving. (I did check my record and it doesn't show up on a public search, but employers have access to some kind of illuminati deep web search data base) but it will always show up on an MVR, which you have to show any trucking employer. Not sure how strict some of those oil rig companies are about O.W.I. convictions?  Most places want at least 7 years to have past. I have applied at some places that excepted 3 years to pass, but never heard back,  but thought that due to having no recent driving experience and were all local LTL companies (not super gung ho about trucking to start off at the bottom as an OTR driver again)  I was a good truck driver in my time, it's organic or in my DNA.  I would challenge any top super trucker at any oil rig place to some kind of driver rodeo challenge for like some kind of pre employment consideration,  even being out of a truck almost 5 years and know I can drive 50x better than any green driver with a case of beer in me (just kidding, quit drinking over an O.W.I. and swear on a stack bibles I have)  but anyway if those oil fields transports are desperate and pay good I'd be a perfect fit for any job, but main issue is no recent experience and a bad insurance canidate(even though I could jump in a rig tommorow and be right back at it)  but do like routine and regularity, which those oil field driving jobs don't seem have, I'd be bored to death with all that waiting, but could assimilate, adapt and overcome.

The first time, I went in with lots of on the job skills, but did not study the code book to the level needed for doing well on the written exam.  The second time, I aced the exam due to really knowing the sections of the plumbing code that are tested on the Journeyman's exam. commentText: How to identify an inexperienced truck driver:   did you hear him giving fuel to the engine before he let out the clutch?  That is not required with a diesel engine.  There is a servo in the fuel pump that adds fuel to keep the motor running as you let out the clutch.   When driving them in hill country, it will pull the throttle out from under your foot as it adds fuel to accommodate for the additional hill pulling power.  Drivers call it "the sweet spot" in the accelerator.   It's how you know you aren't wasting fuel, when the truck is allowed to function as it is designed to function.
